<subSubSection id="133789861F9C3C9F3B726BF4FA82C602" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E1292EDB69FFEFCBDC9C836C322D1889" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">General distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="73EC579BE4A6DE20AF3BF01B212C75C0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Central Asia south to North Himalaya and North Tibet. For a long time, 
<taxonomicName id="DF46D0E54CA2F6C6268A85E053F8F8BA" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. pamiricum" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="pamiricum">
<emphasis id="0CB27F23CCFC9D96488CF16AFF3A86B8" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">C. pamiricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been considered endemic to Pamir (
<bibRefCitation id="DC2383C67B25487FFD4EB3874059896B" author="Iljin, MM" editor="Shishkin, BK" journalOrPublisher="6. Akademiya Nauk, Moscow-Leningrad" pageId="127" pageNumber="128" pagination="2 - 354" refId="B47" refString="Iljin, MM, 1936. Chenopodiaceae. In: Shishkin, BK, Ed., Flora of USSR, Vol. 6. Akademiya Nauk, Moscow-Leningrad: 2 - 354" title="Chenopodiaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of USSR, Vol." year="1936">Iljin 1936</bibRefCitation>
, 
